{"id":"e6af01ff-7a34-4bde-97da-67fa3d57bf28","type":"heading","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left","level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Community and Societal Stigma","styles":{}}],"children":[{"id":"4b16a6b8-0711-4088-b32d-71203a061712","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Due to the stigma surrounding PTSD, individuals with the condition may be looked down upon by others. People may hold false beliefs about PTSD, causing them to treat those with the condition and their families differently. Unfortunately, stigma can also extend to other aspects of a person's identity, including race, sexuality, gender identity, religion, and disability status [2] [4].","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"aa9f9c0b-cf18-406e-8e54-2ecceb3f2dfd","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[],"children":[]},{"id":"2364cc2d-2ab0-4c28-a245-7612edb616d2","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Misconceptions about mental health symptoms and PTSD can lead to stigmatization by families and the broader community. Additionally, society often associates the condition with military veterans and violence, adding further stigma to PTSD, and reinforcing the assumption that it only affects military veterans or those who have experienced violence [2] [6].","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"a7b35b5d-f227-4b35-85ae-0a86b32d0632","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[],"children":[]},{"id":"7cd05573-6d29-459f-8960-3cbf9ce7bfeb","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Even well-intentioned people may feel uncomfortable upon learning someone has PTSD, making it difficult for that person to find a job or housing [4].","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"bee56304-6780-4d92-819a-2475e596194c","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[],"children":[]},{"id":"b0a87046-b2c2-4e0a-9faf-6836917560e9","type":"paragraph","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Stigma occurs when others [4]:","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"73cd0338-98c7-4517-bbdc-ddb9d143534c","type":"bulletListItem","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Don't understand PTSD","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"8b72764a-5c49-443d-a397-592aaef69dbd","type":"bulletListItem","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Don't realize PTSD is a treatable illness","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"d44cdbf9-0fdb-43fd-b039-6e86510e5f11","type":"bulletListItem","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Think mental illness is \"your own fault\" or something you can \"get over\"","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"2a886ae2-7e9a-435b-bd50-2624e219d617","type":"bulletListItem","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Are afraid they might catch what you have","styles":{}}],"children":[]},{"id":"f1ab1940-942c-4aaa-a3a8-b0ebaf05e018","type":"bulletListItem","props":{"textColor":"default","backgroundColor":"default","textAlignment":"left"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Believe PTSD makes you dangerous","styles":{}}],"children":[]}]}